 types)\n61:- [ ] WS2-03 Implement GGUF tensor info reader (name, dims, type, offset)\n62:- [ ] WS2-04 Implement tensor data loader (read quantized blocks from file into memory)\n63:- [ ] WS2-05 Add GGUF validation tool (print model info, tensor list, total size)\n65:### WS3 — Quantization Kernels\n66:- [ ] WS3-01 Implement Q4_0 block structure (32 values per block, 1 scale float16)\n67:- [ ] WS3-02 Implement Q4_0 dequantize (block -> integer array)\n68:- [ ] WS3-03 Implement Q4_0 dot product (quantized vec * quantized vec -> scalar)\n69:- [ ] WS3-04 Implement Q8_0 block structure and dequantize\n70:- [ ] WS3-05 Implement Q8_0 dot product\n71:- [ ] WS3-06 AVX2 optimized Q4_0 dot product (inline asm)\n72:- [ ] WS3-07 AVX2 optimized Q8_0 dot product (inline asm)\n73:- [ ] WS3-08 Benchmark: Q4_0 dot product ops/sec (naive vs AVX2)\n75:### WS4 — Matrix Operations\n76:- [ ] WS4-01 Implement naive matmul (quantized input, integer accumulator)\n77:- [ ] WS4-02 Implement row-major / col-major layout handling\n78:- [ ] WS4-03 AVX2 tiled matmul (cache-friendly blocking)\n79:- [ ] WS4-04 Implement element-wise operations (add, mul, scale)\n80:- [ ] WS4-05 Benchmark: matmul GOPS for typical LLM dimensions (4096x4096)\n82:### WS5 — LLaMA Forward Pass\n83:- [ ] WS5-01 Implement RoPE (Rotary Position Embedding) in integer math\n84:- [ ] WS5-02 Implement GQA (Grouped Query Attention) — Q/K/V projection, score, softmax, output\n85:- [ ] WS5-03 Implement SwiGLU FFN (gate * up projection, silu activation, down projection)\n86:- [ ] WS5-04 Implement transformer block (attention + FFN + residual + RMSNorm)\n87:- [ ] WS5-05 Implement full forward pass (embed -> N blocks -> final norm -> logits)\n88:- [ ] WS5-06 Implement KV cache for autoregressive generation\n89:- [ ] WS5-07 Validation: compare logits against llama.cpp for first token of known prompt\n91:### WS6 — Tokenizer\n92:- [ ] WS6-01 Implement BPE vocabulary loader from GGUF metadata\n93:- [ ] WS6-02 Implement BPE encode (text -> token IDs)\n94:- [ ] WS6-03 Implement BPE decode (token IDs -> text)\n95:- [ ] WS6-04 Handle special tokens (BOS, EOS, padding)\n96:- [ ] WS6-05 Validation: tokenize/detokenize round-trip matches llama.cpp\n98:### WS7 — Sampling & Generation\n99:- [ ] WS7-01 Implement temperature scaling on logits\n100:- [ ] WS7-02 Implement top-k sampling\n101:- [ ] WS7-03 Implement top-p (nucleus) sampling\n102:- [ ] WS7-04 Implement repetition penalty\n103:- [ ] WS7-05 Implement autoregressive generation loop (prompt -> tokens one at a time)\n104:- [ ] WS7-06 Implement `Inference(prompt, max_tokens, temp, top_k, top_p);` HolyC API\n106:### WS8 — Integration & Polish\n107:- [ ] WS8-01 End-to-end test: load TinyLlama Q4_0, generate 50 tokens, compare quality\n108:- [ ] WS8-02 Memory usage profiling and optimization\n109:- [ ] WS8-03 Book of Truth integration hooks (log model load, each token, anomalies)\n110:- [ ] WS8-04 Interactive mode with streaming token output to TempleOS console\n111:- [ ] WS8-05 Performance tuning: identify and optimize top-5 hottest functions\n112:- [ ] WS8-06 Documentation: user guide for loading models and running inference\n114:### WS9 — GPU Compute Partition (IOMMU-Safe, Book-of-Truth-Audited)\n118:- [ ] WS9-01 GPU threat model: DMA risks, firmware opacity, MMIO attack surface, IOMMU bypass vectors\n119:- [ ] WS9-02 IOMMU (VT-d/AMD-Vi) initialization and enforcement — mandatory, no GPU without it\n120:- [ ] WS9-03 GPU memory partition design — dedicated physical region, never overlaps kernel/log pages\n121:- [ ] WS9-04 Explicit copy-in/copy-out protocol — CPU copies tensors to GPU region, triggers compute, copies results\n122:- [ ] WS9-05 PCIe device enumeration in HolyC — discover GPU via config space, map BARs\n123:- [ ] WS9-06 GPU command submission interface — minimal ring buffer, no proprietary driver\n124:- [ ] WS9-07 MMIO register map for target GPU compute dispatch (start with virtio-gpu or simple compute)\n125:- [ ] WS9-08 Book of Truth hooks: